Chronic effects of cannabis

For this analysis, I compared the heart rate at during the ‘predose’ window across dosage groups using time in days as a continuous covariate. Data from dosing days and non-dosing days were included since we are only looking at the predose window.

Model-based dose group estimates

Observed data

Each line represents an individual mice.

## Warning: Removed 84 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).

Based on my understanding of the study design, the 3 dosage groups should not differ in heart rate at day 1 during the predose window because none of the animals would have received any cannabis prior to that time point.

Since this graphic made it look like the dosage groups differed at day 1, I tested that directly.

Omnibus p-value for dosage effect: 0.931

There are no significant differences in starting heart rate between the three dose levels.

contrast estimate SE df t.ratio p.value
Low - Med 27.871429 102.5599 3 0.2717576 0.9606319
Low - High 37.842857 102.5599 3 0.3689830 0.9294035
Med - High 9.971429 102.5599 3 0.0972254 0.9948111

Acute Effects of Cannabis on heart rate

To examine the acute effects (i.e., within a treatment day) of cannabis, data points were limited to those collected during a ‘dose’ day.

Initial Acute Effect of Cannabis on heart rate

First, the initial acute effects of cannabis were assessed by only focusing on changes in heart rate across different windows of time on the first study day that mice were exposed to cannabis

Two-Way ANOVA Results

Based on the significant interaction effect, the model suggest that the effect of the within-day time window differs between doses.
